
[1]scorch

   SCORCH, v.t.

   1. To burn superficially; to subject to a degree of heat that changes
   the color of a thing, or both the color and texture of the surface.
   Fire will scorch linen or cotton very speedily in extremely cold
   weather.

   2. To burn; to affect painfully with heat. Scorched with the burning
   sun or burning sands of Africa.

   SCORCH, v.i. To be burnt on the surface; to be parched; to be dried up.

   Scatter a little mungy straw and fern among your seedlings, to prevent
   the roots from scorching.
